LDR-Based Light Intensity Monitor with LCD (Arduino)

This project demonstrates how to measure ambient light intensity using an LDR (Light Dependent Resistor) and display the results on a 16×2 LCD using an Arduino. The system continuously reads the light level through an analog input and categorizes the environment as Bright, Normal, or Dark based on predefined threshold values.

The measured sensor value is displayed on the LCD along with the corresponding light condition, providing a simple real-time light monitoring system.

Features
Reads ambient light intensity using an LDR.
Displays the light level on a 16×2 LCD.
Classifies the environment as Bright, Normal, or Dark.
Updates readings continuously in real time.
Demonstrates analog sensor interfacing and LCD communication.

Working Principle
The LDR forms a voltage divider with a resistor, producing a voltage proportional to the surrounding light intensity.
The Arduino reads this voltage using the analog input pin (A0) through the analogRead() function.
Based on the sensor value:
Values above 700 are displayed as BRIGHT.
Values between 400 and 700 are displayed as NORMAL.
Values below 400 are displayed as DARK.
The LCD displays:
The current light condition on the first row.
The raw LDR sensor value on the second row.
The display is refreshed every 500 milliseconds to provide real-time updates.
